reviews.review_text: Good show This is a pretty good show & this is the best version with the less cuts only one in Row Jimmy.

this IS pretty good... ...and i think the recording is actually very good.  a little quiet, but really very clear and balanced.  really good first set (best brother esau ever?), and H>S>F is good here as well.  i had this tape for years, and now i'm pretty sure it was this source.  left the first set in a car i was forced to abandon (POS!) in nebraska on a cross country trip in '90.  nice to hear it again.  and now i have it back!

thanks...

by by coliseum they imploded this place 2 years ago, check out this awesome video of it 

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nctvL-eOzSs&feature=related

all about the second set i woke up for deal to close the first set... very hot deal.
but i really liked the second set: when you look at it, not necessarily a top tier song selection but really well put together and an unexpected pleasure. set 2 w/ appropriate amount of energy to engage mind and soul. you know what i mean... and bobby kinda engages the folk down front, which is fun.

Smoking hot playing, strong energy and PHIL! I was at this show, but it being 37 years ago, it was lost to me over the fog of time.

Listened to it tonight. I’m flabbergasted the boys could light it up like this, at an unremarkable tour stop in an unremarkable arena, on an unremarkable Friday night. But light it up they did.

Song selection is solid. The energy is a 10 out of 10. Listen to Deal straight away. That ending.

The sound on this recording captures the Spring ‘83 sound perfectly. Love Jerry’s guitar tone. Aggressive and well-enunciated singing. Jerry’s solos are right on the money. And Phil is having at it this whole show. The Phil Bombs are everywhere.

The GD played so many shows. They can be forgiven for calling it in once in a while. I mean this date has no historical importance. It’s just another gig, in New Haven. But they delivered the magic on this night.

I love the Grateful Dead.
